00:08:29.600 --> 00:08:34.960
overused quote when you're learning about data visualization. But let me read it to you. It's,

00:08:34.960 --> 00:08:41.520
the greatest value of a picture is when it forces us to notice what we never expected to see.

00:08:42.479 --> 00:08:46.479
Now, this is a very old idea. This is something that was said by John Tukey,

00:08:46.479 --> 00:08:53.520
I think, like 50-ish years ago. And there's a, you can interpret the quote in different ways,

00:08:53.520 --> 00:08:59.280
but the way that I interpret it is that the real value of data visualization is the element of

00:08:59.280 --> 00:09:07.359
surprise. When you set out to do a graph, challenging your assumptions is the whole point,

00:09:07.359 --> 00:09:14.559
I would say. When you start a data visualization, when you start a data analysis project,

00:09:14.559 --> 00:09:22.159
you're probably going to have some ideas about what you're going to find, what your intuition

00:09:22.719 --> 00:09:27.359
is going to tell you. There's probably all sorts of graphs that you already have in your mind

00:09:27.919 --> 00:09:34.880
before you see them on the screen. Challenging those assumptions is the whole point. You want

00:09:34.880 --> 00:09:40.479
to prove yourself wrong when you're doing analysis. Because graphs that prove your point

00:09:41.039 --> 00:09:47.280
have little to no value in my mind. They have some value, they can be decorative,

00:09:47.280 --> 00:09:53.119
they can grab people's attention, they're nice to look at. But if you want insight from a graph,

00:09:53.119 --> 00:09:58.159
you need it to prove you're wrong. And that's something that I learned very late

00:09:58.719 --> 00:10:05.520
in my own data literacy journey. So yeah, that's one important thing.

00:10:07.119 --> 00:10:12.719
